1 Numerical datatype
1.1 integer and float
  • integers (can be positive or negative whole number)
    • e.g. 50, -390
    • int value = -5;
    • unsigned int num = 10;
    • long int bigValue = - 49322032;
    • unsigned long biggish = 59302012;
  • floating-point: numbers that can have fractional parts are represented as floating point (or float) values. (zb2.7 Floating-point numbers (double)
    • has decimal point, even the decimal part is 0, eg. 3.0
    • float voltage = 3.3;
    • double temp = 79.5;

Question: Why do we need two number types?

Ans:

  • Values that represent counts cant be fractional (you cant have 3 quarters). Integer variables are typically used for values that are counted, like 42 cars, 10 pizzas, or -95 days.
  • Most mathematical algorithms are very efficient with integers
  • Floating-point variables are typically used for measurements, like 98.6 degrees, 0.00001 meters, or -55.667 degrees. The float type stores only an approximation to the real number being represented!

1.3 Integer division and modulo

see zb2.11 Integer division and modulo

  • When both operands of $/$ are integers, the operator performs integer division, which does not generate any fraction.
  • The modulo operator (%) evaluates the remainder of the division of two integer operands.

integer division / and modulus (remainder) %¶

In integer division and modulus, the dividend (11 in the example) is divided by the divisor (4) into an integer quotient (2) and a remainder (3). The integer quotient operation is referred to as integer division, (so 11 / 4 is 2 ) and the integer remainder operation is the modulus (so 11 % 4 is 3)

Modulo(%)

The modulo operator (%) evaluates the remainder of the division of two integer operands. Ex: 23 % 10 is 3.

  • 24 % 10 is 4. Reason: 24 / 10 is 2 with remainder 4.
  • 50 % 50 is 0. Reason: 50 / 50 is 1 with remainder 0.
  • 1 % 2 is 1. Reason: 1 / 2 is 0 with remainder 1.
  • 10 % 4.0 is not valid. "Remainder" only makes sense for integer operands
Division (/)

Floating-point division¶

The $/$ operator performs floating-point division if at least one operand is a floating-point type.

  • If both operands of / are integers, the operator performs integer division: No fractional part is generated. Thus 10 / 4 is 2, not 2.5. And 3 / 4 is 0, not 0.75.
  • Programmers may forget integer division, causing strange logic errors. (1/2) b h is always (0) b h or 0. And c (9/5) + 32 is always c (1) + 32.
  • The same applies for integer variables. No fraction is generated for y = w / x if w and x are int type, even if y is a floating-point type.
  • If at least one operand of / is a floating-point type, then floating-point division occurs. So if int w = 10 and double x = 4.0, then w / x is 2.5.
In [3]:
//Example 1-2
#include <stdio.h>
int main() 
{
    int y;
    float z; 
    
    //integer division
    y = 10 / 4; 
    z = 10 / 4; //assign an integer to a float
    
    //We use format specifier %d for integer, %f for float
    printf("10/4 is %d, y is %d , z is %f\n", 10 / 4, y, z);
    
    //float division: 10/4.0 will produce a float
    y = 10 / 4.0; //assign a float to int will discard the decimal part 
    z = 10 / 4.0; 
    
    printf("10/4.0 is %f, y is %d , z is %f\n", 10 / 4.0, y, z);
    
    //can we do this?
    //printf("y is %f\n", y);
    return 0;
}

10/4 is 2, y is 2 , z is 2.000000
10/4.0 is 2.500000, y is 2 , z is 2.500000
Division: Divide by 0
  • For integer division, the second operand of / or % must never be 0, because division by 0 is mathematically undefined. A divide-by-zero error occurs at runtime if a divisor is 0, causing a program to terminate
  • any number $/0$ or %0 is undefined, cause program to terminate
In [30]:
//Example 1-3
#include <stdio.h>
int main(){
    
    printf("23 %% 3 / 4 = %d\n", 23 % 3 / 4); 
    printf("23 %% (3 / 4) will cause ERROR, why?\n");
    printf("23 / 3 %% 4 = %d\n", 23 / 3 % 4); 
    printf("23 / 3 / 4 = %d\n", 23 / 3 / 4);
    printf("23.0 / 3 / 4 = %f (using %%f)\n", 23.0 / 3 / 4);
    
    return 0;
}

23 % 3 / 4 = 0
23 % (3 / 4) will cause ERROR, why?
23 / 3 % 4 = 3
23 / 3 / 4 = 1
23.0 / 3 / 4 = 1.916667 (using %f)

1.4 Type conversions

see zb2.12 Type conversions

Implicit conversion

A type conversion is a conversion of one data type to another, such as an int to a float. The compiler automatically performs several common conversions between int and float types, such automatic conversion known as implicit conversion.

  • For an arithmetic operator like + or *, if either operand is a float, the other is automatically converted to float, and then a floating-point operation is performed.

  • For assignments, the right side type is converted to the left side type.

    • int-to-float conversion is straightforward: 25 becomes 25.0.

    • float-to-int conversion just drops the fraction: 4.9 becomes 4.

see see zyBook2.12 for examples¶

A calculation sometimes must mix integer and floating-point numbers. For example, given that about 50.4% of human births are males, then 0.504 * numBirths calculates the number of expected males in numBirths births. If numBirths is an int variable (int because the number of births is countable), then the expression combines a floating-point and integer.

In [12]:
//Example 1-4a
#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    
    int numBirths = 10;
    float maleBirthRate = 0.54;
    
    
    //%d does not work for float (maleBirthRate * numBirths is a float)
    printf("maleBirths = %f", maleBirthRate * numBirths);  
    
    
    return 0;
}

maleBirths = 5.400000
In [7]:
//Example 1-4b

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
    
    int maleBirths;
    float numBirths = 10.0;
    float maleBirthRate = 0.54; //we expected to see 6 males
    maleBirths = maleBirthRate * numBirths;
    
    // this works! because maleBirths is an integer, how about the value?
    printf("maleBirths = %d", maleBirths);
    
    return 0;
}

maleBirths = 5

//Example 1-4c
//Using math function ceil() to round the results 
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>
int main() {
    
    int maleBirths, numBirths = 10;
    float maleBirthRate = 0.504;
    maleBirths = ceil(maleBirthRate * numBirths);
    
    printf("maleBirths = %d", maleBirths);
    
    return 0;
}

maleBirths = 3
Type casting

A programmer sometimes needs to explicitly convert an item's type.

  • Ex: If a program needs a floating-point result from dividing two integers, (see floating division 9/4) then at least one of the integers needs to be converted to float so floating-point division is performed (9/4.0 or 9.0/4). Otherwise, integer division is performed, evaluating to only the quotient and ignoring the remainder.

  • A type cast explicitly converts a value of one type to another type.

  • A programmer can precede an expression with (type) to convert the expression's value to the indicated type.

    • Ex: If myIntVar is 7, then (float)myIntVar converts int 7 to float 7.0.
    • Ex: If myFloatVar is 7.8, then (int)myFloatVar converts float 7.8 to int 7.

  • Example: see zyBook2.12.1

In [9]:
//Example 1-5

    printf("%.2f", (float)myIntVar);

    printf("%f", myF * 2);
    myIntVar = myF * 2;

    printf("\n%d", (int)(myF * 100));

}

2 Data representation in computer

2.1 Number representation and conversion

  • Number representation and conversion

    • Decimal is a numbering system with base 10
    • Binary is a numbering system with base 2
    • Hexadecimal is a numbering system with base 16
    • Octal is a numbering system with base 8

  • see dataRepresentation.pdf for signed & unsigned integer conversion among decimal, binary and hexadecimal

2.2 Integer representation in computer
  • Numbers that are used in mathematical calculations
    • If a computer needs to do math with a number it will store that number using the appropriate binary representation of the number.
    • This makes it easier for the computer to perform mathematical calculations with the number.
    • Example: 5 would be stored as 00000101 
       and 53 would be 00110101

2.3 Character representation in computer

ASCII system¶

ASCII (American Standard Code for Information Interchange) uses decimal numbers 0 through 127 to represent the characters typically found on an (American) computer keyboard, and control codes that are used to coordinate

  • letters AZ are represented by the decimal values 6590, the lowercase versions have decimal values 97122. -ASCII code stored in 1 byte(8 bits) memory, see ASCII table

  • Numbers that are NOT used in mathematical calculations
    • If the computer does NOT need to do math with the number (e.g. a zip code) then it will generally store the number using the ASCII values of the digits.
    • Example: 5 would be stored using its ASCII value of 53 which is represented in binary as 00110101

Unicode: （FYI)¶

  • a much larger standard that includes support for the characters of nearly all written languages, Unicode defines (less than) $2^{21}$characters,
  • Python supports Unicode (1,000,000+ characters)
  • Unicode is a superset of ASCII, and the numbers 0127 have the same meaning in ASCII as they have in Unicode.
  • there are numerous ways of storing Unicode characters in byte sequences, such as UTF-32 and UTF-8.
  • UTF-8 and UTF-16 are variable length encodings.
  • In UTF-8, a character may occupy a minimum of 8 bits. In UTF-16, a character length starts with 16 bits.
  • Both ASCII and Unicode are standardized encodings of written characters as numeric codes
  • unicode list, or unicode charts

We will stick with the ASCII (1 byte) character set in this course¶

  • 'A' is stored as 0b01000001, 65 in decimal 0x41 for hexadecimal , and 101 in octal
  • hexadecimal is base-16 representation, and octal is base-8 representation

we can use sizeof() to get the size of each datatype allocated in the memory. sizeof() will return an unsigned long integer, use %lu as specifier in printf()

3.4 printf() formatting placeholder

  • Common data types and their format specifiers (placeholders) are:

    • int - integer (%d or %i)
    • char - character (%c)
    • short int - short integer (%hd)
    • unsigned int - 0 and. positive integer (%u)
    • long - long integer (%ld)
    • float - float number (%f)
    • double - long float (%lf)
    • String - (often used in Arduino C, e.g. String nameOfAccountHolder = "James Bond";)

  • %d is the placeholder for the value of integer variable age ### (Escape sequence)

  • see zyBook Table 2.14.2 for Common escape sequences.

    • %% for %
  • other placeholders you will see
    • %p dispaly a pointer
    • %s String of characters

  • other data types are: void, signed int, etc ,

  • Please refer to data type in C for example of data type in standard C

The link shown here can be used go get more information on the printf and formatting output.

%[ flags ][ width ][.precision ][ length ]type

  • Flags (FYI)
    • $-$ left-justify
    • $+$ generate a plus sign for positive values
    • $\#$ puts a leading 0 on an octal value and 0x on a hex value
    • 0 pad a number with leading zeros
  • Width (FYI)
    • Minimum number of characters to generate
  • Precision
    • Float: Round to specified decimal places
  • Length
    • l long
  • Type
    • d or i int
    • f float
    • x or X hexadecimal
    • o octal
    • c character
    • u unsigned
    • s string
    • % print a %
In [5]:
//Example 3-3 
#include <stdio.h>
int main(){
    printf("[%5d] [%+05d] [%#5o] [%#7x]\n", 123,123, 123, 123);  //FYI
    printf("[%f] [%9.2f] [%3.2f] [%5.0f%%] [%5.1f]\n", 123.456, 123.456, //required in CSCI218
           123.456, 123.456, 123.565);
    return 0;
    
}

[  123] [+0123] [ 0173] [   0x7b]
[123.456000] [   123.46] [123.46] [  123%] [123.6]

In the first printf shown above, 123 is printed using a variety of formats encloses in brackets:

  • %5d specifies to print x with a width of 5 unless x is greater than 5 digits. Leading zeros will print as spaces.
  • %+05d specifies to print x with a width of 5. Leading zeros will print as zeros. A positive number will have a beginning + sign.
  • %#5o specifies a width of 5, octal with a leading zero.
  • %#7x specifies a width of 7, hexadecimal with a leading 0x.

In the second printf, 123.456 is printed in a variety of formats:

  • %f prints a float with 6 decimal precision
  • %5.2f prints a float with a minimum width of 5 places and two decimal places. Notice that 6 characters printed because it would not fit in 5 characters.
  • %5.0f%% prints a float with a minimum of 5 places, no decimal places, and is followed by a single %. Notice the leading spaces before the number.
  • %5.1f%% prints a float with a minimum of 5 places, 1 decimal places with rounding
